column168: A Univar Driver was in the process of moving a customer’s Hazardous Waste from the Univar Waste Transfer Area into a trailer for delivery to the TSDF in Kansas when he noticed that two drums had product leaking out of the top of the steel open-top drums. column168: This has been reported to local FAA and a case will follow with all the identifiable UN numbers, proper shipping names, hazard classes and packing groups.  Right now, all we have is a list of the items found in the shippers belongings.    The shipper was asked in FAI when offering his hunting gear if he had any hazardous materials and he said no.  During offloading the FAI station found a camp stove but was told it was cleaned and purged of all fuel.    It was carried by highway to ANC where it was caught in the Northern Air Cargo facility by Duane Zutz.  It's final destination is Kodiak, AK.    These items undeclared are:  42 aerial flares  4 pcs trioxane  4 bxs ammunition  6 rounds ammunition loose in a baggie  12 rounds stored in speed loaders  2 bxs strike anywhere matches  1 box safety matches  2 aerosol cans of personal sprays  1 tube flammable Shoo-Goo  2 lanterns with residue coleman fuel  5 lighters
column169: We have had a discussion with the FAI office on enhancing awareness of undeclared hazardous materials.    A couple of these awareness points are to ask many questions of the shipper regarding hazardous materials.  Also, the enhanced inspecting of hunting shipments before being introduced into the transportation system by placing these shipments on hold until they can be inspected sufficiently.

column162: SENIOR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND COMPLIANCE
column168: The source of the release was found to be originating from the manway seal. The 6 bolt manway was found with two slightly loose bolts which when tightened approx 1/4 turn secured the manway seal and stopped the leak. This residue tank car was found with 91 psi of compressed air remaining in the tank. When this pressure relieved through the loose manway closure it also carried ammonia odor from the residue. All other closures were inspected and found to be properly secured. Agencies responding: East Baton Rouge Fire Department, Louisiana State Police and Louisiana Department of Environmental Quality. The Chemtrec notification was made to the shipper and consignee as found on the railroad waybill. Chemtrec call returned by Southern Ionics, their Sam White, 662)295-1075, swhite@southernionics.com and Terra Nitrogen, their Jeff Seebrech (712)253-8535. However it was later learned that Exxonmobil actually unloaded this car and offered it into transportation (aka shipper). Exxonmobil was later notified directly, to their Brian Blakemore. Both Exxonmobil and Terra Nitrogen have been asked to provide feedback as to why it's necessary to pressurize vessel to ~100 psi to unload lading. If continued, this pressure in a general service tank car coupled with the low odor threshold of ammonia solution provides high probability of recurrence. Exxonmobil was asked to reevaluate their unloading process to see if car can be unloaded with ~10-15 psi.     KCS emergency mitigation services were activated to provide for special switching for safety isolation, yard service interruption, Critical Incident Desk notifications, emergency response, dedicated internal management oversight, train/yard crew delay, and regulatory reporting as appropriate.  KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 and KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 may apply as services require.    Note to report, item 27, amount in package, was estimated. This action required by preparer to facilitate data acceptance by defective DOT IT system edits. Specifically, this estimated quantity was required: (1)because the shippers only provided bulk quantities on shipping paper, as "1 Tank Car", per DOT requirements; and (2)because the DOT e-system requires data in this field to facilitate report acceptance.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. For non-accident releases (a.k.a. packages or closure defects such as this), shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.

column168: A truck picked up a shipment of 10 drums that were stored outdoors.  The drums were dirty/muddy at the time of pickup.  They were not leaking at the time of pickup.  When the driver arrived at his home terminal, he noticed a drum was leaking a small amount of liquid while doing his routine post trip inspection.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, the drums were unloaded onto the dock where they were cleaned off.  It was then found that 5 of the drums had pinhole leaks.  All of the drums in the shipment were old and corroded and were overpacked into suitable salvage containers.  The absorbent material used to clean up the spilled material and to clean off the drums was also put into the salvage drums.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer for the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The driver did not thoroughly inspect the containers at the time of pickup.  The mud and dirt should have been cleaned off at the customer's site to inspect for pinhole leaks, etc...  The driver was given a written warning and suspension.

column168: Found the manway cover was not secured from origin, all bolts down. The car was pulled from shipper facility ay 1:30am on 10/09/10 and was received at KCS Mossville yard at 3:32am. When car was coupled in yard the manway cover flew open from lading surge. The manway gasket landed on the ground. 63 gallons of lading was released. PPG responded to the site along with KCS responders and secured the manway cover and gasket. PPG neutalized the released material.     KCS emergency mitigation services were activated to provide for special switching for safety isolation, yard service interruption, Critical Incident Desk notifications, emergency response, dedicated internal management oversight, train/yard crew delay, and regulatory reporting as appropriate.  KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 and KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 may apply as services require.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. For non-accident releases (a.k.a. packages or closure defects such as this), shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.

column168: On 10/07/2010 at 06:00 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Radnor yard in Nashville, TN, discovered CTCX 732691, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., leaking from the bottom of the rail car. The car was isolated in the rail yard away from CSXT employees, and the shipper was notified thru CHEMTREC Report 2010-10-07-00040. The shipper's, Abengoa Bioenergy, representative, Brad Ross 618-610-9658, responded to the call. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and discovered product was leaking from the bottom outlet cap. HEPACO secured the leak by opening and closing the bottom outlet handle and tightening the bottom outlet cap. The leak was secured and the car was released to destination.     This incident did require a special switch move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.     Cause Code: 149  NARRI Code: 5 (3+3+0) x (2+0) = 60

I THEN NOTICED THAT THE WOODEN BOX WAS PRODUCING VISIBLE SMOKE. SO BY FOLLOWING MY DECISION TREE I TOLD ERNIE TO CONTACT PE IMMEDIATETLY. ERNIE THEN INSTRUCTED ME TO GO BACK TO THE PSC AREA TO BRING BACK AN SCBA IN CASE IT WAS NEEDED. ONCE PE WAS INVOLVED THEY THEN PROCEEDED TO REPORT IT TO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. column168: The trailer was parked in our yard, empty of all liquid, containing vapors only, noted at 100 psi. Our mechanic detected a slight ammonia odor during the yard walk around inspection. The release was not audible, nor easy to locate. Finally he tracked the odor to the top of the trailer, the 3 ½” valve was leaking, discovered by soapy water.     The trailer was made secure and relieved of all pressure, bleeding off through our water scrubber system.     Inspection of the valve “KOREA T40644.” There appears to be visible material bulging from the underside seat area. We have not dismantled but plan to hand over the complete valve to a 3 rd party to do so.
column169: Made in Korea, assembled in Mexico? We collectily as an industry and our govermant are going to have to demand better quality control. The equipment that is suppose to protect us all, is not doing the job.

column168: Approximately 15 gallons of fuel dye (UNISOL(R) Liquid REd BK-50) was released onto an asphalt parking lot over a 2 mile roadway and at 330 Wilson Road, South, Columbus Ohio, 43204.  The main area impacted at the facility was about 2 ft. by 180 ft.  A cleanup contractor (EMS) was dispatched to contain and remediate the release.  Mortar mix was applied to the main release area at the facility.  The waste absorbent was then collected and tranferred to 55-gallon drums.  A total of 3 drums of waste were generated as a result of the release.  The Ohio EPA was consulted about cleaning the roadway.  EPA direction was to clean any material that was not dry.  The roadway was inspected and found to be dry, so no further action was required.

column168: A tanker temporarily stored at the Eagle Ford facility overturned onto the ground as a result of landing gear sinking through the ground.  It released and estimated 60 gallons of UN3082 (methyldiethanolamine/diethanolamine aqueous solution) onto soils at the Eagle Ford facility. The contractor transferred the remaining product in the tanker and the facility utilized a backhoe to create a berm around the spill. The impacted soils were excavated and containerized for disposal.  No storm drains or surface waters were impacted as a result of this release.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While making a delivery to Lincoln Electric in Mentor, Ohio, approximately 40 gallons of free liquid were released as a result of a hose failure.  The release impacted a gravel/soil area of the facility.  Lincoln Electric personnel applied soda ash to the puddles of sulfuric acid.  Lincoln Electric personnel utilized a power floor sweeper washer to recover the neutralized acid.  Lincoln Environmental off-loaded the generated liquids into their on-site waste water treatment facility for disposal. The Ohio Environmental Protection Agency was on-site and approved this method of disposal.  The Ohio Environmental Protection Agency also field tested the surfaces where the spill occurred with PH paper and obtained neutral readings.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However,  Bridgeland Terminals Limited will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column169: PLACE DUNNAGE UNDER DRUMS, BAGS, PAILS AND TOTES TO PREVENT SHARP OR POINTED OBJECTS FROM PUNCTURING THE BOTTOM.  PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS OR PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD EAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

A driver was breaking his trailer and was crossing the dock at the Con-way facility. He ran directly into the skid of 4 drums of organic oxidizer. The result was the drums were pushed of the pallet causing one of the drums to be punctured about a foot from the bottom of the drum causing a two gal leak. We immediately called the incident into Safety and the State Police. The local fire department was also notified. We continued with the cleanup process as directed by the State Police to package in an overpack drum. 5 hours later there was a reaction with the metal overpack causing an explosion. Emergency response numbers were called and the facility was evacuated with no injuries. The spill was cleaned up by Jones Brothers. The facility was reopened 7 hours after the evacuation that occurred around 12:30 am.
column169: Steps have been made to insure that this does not occur. A hazmat checklist will be followed to insure all numbers are called to keep this from happening. Also the driver will be re-trained on his forklift certification before breaking freight again.

column168: R&L Carriers contacted ERTS to manage a paint release in a trailer from an apparent load shift. ERTS dispatched a contractor to the site, who over packed the leaking pail and 8 others that looked damaged. They then cleaned up the trailer with absorbents and containerized the clean up debris in the same over pack. The drum was then transported back to the terminal for shipper's disposition.

A driver was picking up shipments of hazardous waste from multiple stops.  While loading at the second location, the shipper's personnel punctured a drum already on the truck from another generator with the forklift blade.  The shipper's response crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and immediately contained the spill.  The drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage drum along with the absorbent materials used to clean up the spill.  The trailer then continued on his pickup route without further incident.
column169: The shipper will advise their personnel to use better care when loading trailers.

column168: A driver picked up a load on a tanker trailer and returned to the containment area of the terminal for the night.  While performing a routine post trip inspection, he noticed a small leak dripping from the cap of the rear valve.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, he placed a bucket under the leaking cap and slowly removed the cap.  Approximately 1 gallon of liquid was released into the bucket and a small amount onto the containment pad.  The area was cleaned with a suitable absorbent material and the leaking material and cleanup debris was placed into a suitable salvage container.  After no more material leaked, the cap was placed back onto the valve.  The load and salvage material was then taken to the intended waste disposal facility where it was delivered without further incident.
column169: The tanker was loaded by the shipper.  It is believed that they did not clear the valve prior to capping the valve.  The tanker was not leaking when the driver picked it up.  The shipper was notified of the incident and advised that they would investigate with the person who loaded the tanker.

column168: On 10/07/2010 at 10:49 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Radnor yard in Nashville, TN, discovered PLMX 135237, a residue tank car of Ammonia, Anhydrous, leaking from the top of the rail car. The car was isolated in the rail yard away from CSXT employees and the shipper was notified thru CHEMTREC Report 2010-10-07-00119, Angie King 813-261-0600.  HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and discovered product was leaking from the pressure relief device.  HEPACO secured the leak by replacing the O rings on the pressure relief device cap. The leak was secured and the car was released to destination.     This incident did require a special switch move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is required for this incident.     Cause Code: 414  NARRI Code: 5 (4+9+2) x (2+0) = 150

On 10/08/10 at 21:07 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Avon yard in Avon, IN, discovered   UTLX 900362, a loaded tank car of Sulfur Dioxide, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and Calabrian, the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC Report 2010-10-08-00220. The local Fire Department, IDEM, and NRC were also notified. Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a leak between the pressure plate and the nozzle. The issue identified was discussed with the shipper's representative, Les Hanna 409-579-3582. SPSI and Summit Environmental personnel stablized the leak and transferred the product into UTLX 27440. The cleaned and purged car was home shopped for inspection and repairs.    This incident did require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report will be completed.    Cause Code: 100  NARRI:  5 (5+10+2) x (2+7) = 765

column62: Defective Component or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: A BNSF switch crew switching SRIX 21525 (DOT 111A100W3 tank car) in the railyard, reported a product slosh from this tank cars manway closure. No spillage impacted the ground as it remained on SRIX 21525's tank shell. Movement of SRIX 21525 was stopped. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was notified. The BNSF responder reported that SRIX 21525 was missing all four placards. The intact manway closure shipper seal numbered 2229879 was removed. The tool tight manway swing bolts were loosened to check the condition of the manway gasket and product outage. The product outage was deemed appropriate. The manway gasket was found deteriorated and missing a section of the gasket (approximate 4 inch section). The deteriorated gasket didn't provide a good seal and allowed product to escape at the manway closure during rail movement. The responder replaced the manway gasket in kind, closed the manway lid and tool tightened all 8 manway swing bolts. BNSF seal numbered 1095252 was affixed to the manway closure. The appropriate placarding was applied to all four sides of SRIX 21525. Spillage on the top shell and on safety appliances (side ladders) were wiped/cleaned. Response was concluded by 0450 hrs. CDT, 10/21/2010.  The side specification stencil on SRIX 21525 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2002 and next due in 2012.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

Driver, with the assitance of consignee personnel, was able reach a safety shower for decontamination. EMS was called and transported driver to the hospital for treatment. Changes to prevent a recurrence include more emphasis on following written procedures and field audits to evaluate deviations between written procedures and actual practices. Then we can correct the practice and/or improve the procedures.

column168: our 26,000 GVW straight truck was driving east bound on I94 crossing over Hwy 61 bridge when the driver heard a loud explosion and thought a rear tire had blown. He looked in his rearview mirror and saw liquid coming out of the back of the truck and immediately pulled over onto the shoulder with the truck facing uphill. He got out of the truck and opened the rear of the truck. He saw the tote on the back end of the truck was leaking. He called the office and talked to Joe who told him to call 911. Joe called the Minnesota duty officer and called me. I was only 5 minutes away and headed to the scene to coordinate the response.  The tote was strapped to the wall of the truck about 6 feet from the back door.  The plastic inner packaging burst about 6" from the bottom of the container. The crack is horizontal and approximately 24" long. It follows the top contour of the round opening where the bottom valve is. There is no visible damage to the crack that may have contributed to the failure. It appears that the inner container failed.  The driver put his respirator on and tried to stop the liquid from going down the hill and into the storm sewer using using haz mat spill pads. The liquid did make it down approximately 300 feet from the truck and some material did get into the storm sewer. The St Paul fire department arrived with the Highway Patrol and the St Paul haz mat emergency response team. The fire department took over the site. MN DOT closed 2 of the 3 east bound lanes. The far left lane was left open.  It was determined that sodium bicarbonate would neautralize the bisulfite solution. The St Paul haz mat team had some sodium bicarbonate with them but did not have enough. I called our office and had them send one of our trucks down with a pallet of 50lb bags of sodium bicarbonate. The haz mat team used this to neautralize the solution. Bay West, a private hazardous materials clean up team was called in to clean up the site and the truck. They cleaned up the truck and released it for us to drive it back to our warehouse.  The driver was brought to the emergency room for a check up and to clean some of the liquid off of him. He was released right away.  A car driving east bound had a tie rod break and the car ended up pulling over behind our truck. It had 2 women in it. The liquid ran down the shoulder under their car. They stayed in the car until the haz mat team removed them and brought them to the emergency room for observation.  The Minnesota Pollution Control Agency determined that the liquid did make it into the storm sewer. I was told by the Emergency Response Specialist from the Mediation Division that it did not make it to the Mississippi River but they were not sure how far into the storm sewer it traveled.  The time of the incident was approximately 6 hours.
column169: We are setting up our own hazardous materials containment systems on our trucks to help mitigate any release. These carry a 400  gallon expandable container to put under the truck to catch any release. The kit also contains a Class B suit, respirator, gloves, safety vest and 80 feet of 3" socks. The drivers will all be trained in proper use of all materials.  I would like to provide suggestions for improvements but I do not know how you can predict the catastrophic failure of a container like this. It was tested in June of this year. I have never seen anything like it in my 25 years of being in business. The PHMSA Hazardous Materials investigator that looked at the tote the next day said he had never seen anything like it either.

column168: On 10/12/2010 at approximately 00:39 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Curtis Bay Yard in Baltimore, MD, discovered GATX 59307, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper - PPG, MDE and Baltimore City FD Hazmat were notified via CHEMTREC 2010-10-12-00009. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, along with a CSXT Hazmat Manager, were dispatched to the scene and found a blown rupture disk. HEPACO replaced the disk with like in kind and decontaminated the car of the spilled material. The leak was secured and the car released for transport.    This incident did not require a special switching move.   This incident does not require a QA 7.1 Non conformance report.    Cause Code: 441  NARRI Code: 5 (5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100

column168: On 10/12/2010 at approximately 11:43 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Cumberland yard in Cumberland, MD, discovered UTLX 130207, a loaded tank car of Ferric Chloride Solution, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Kemira Water Solutions, local, state and/or federal agencies as applicable were notified via CHEMTREC 2010-10-12-00120. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that all four (4) bolts on the fill hole were less than tool tight, along with the wrong style and grade of washers to secure the fill hole. HEPACO was able to tighten the nuts to safely move the car to a shop track. The shipper notified Rescar who sent a mobile repair unit out to replace the washers. The tank car was sealed and released for transportation.    This incident did not require a special switching move.  This incident does not require a QA 7.1 Non conformance report.    Cause Code: 224  NARRI: 5 (5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80

column168: On 10/18/2010 at 04:23 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Hamlet Yard in Hamlet, NC, discovered TILX 261457, a residue tank car of Cyclohexanone, emitting a hissing noise from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, DSM Chemicals, was notified via CHEMTREC 2010-10-18-00009. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the cause of the release was due to a round deformity (about the diameter of a manway securement bolt) in the manway cover gasket. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Glen Davis at 706-849-6851. HEPACO replaced the manway gasket and the rail car was released to its destination.     This incident did not require a special switching move. column42: AEROSOLS, NON-FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: On October 28th, 2010, during the examination of export documents offered for transport. The carrier (Seaboard Marine) noticed on an invoice that container FCIU-808684-4 was carrying non-hazardous as well as hazardous cargo (UN 1950 AEROSOLS). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded. We immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. On October 29th, 2010, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and afterward released for transportation.

A package was received from SAES containing multiple items.  The package was opened to verify against the packing list before transferring the items to the final destination.  The package contained a smaller package that was marked and labeled as a UN3089 Metal powders, flammable, n.o.s.  Upon inspection of the packing list and the outer packaging there was no indication that any hazardous materials were included in the shipment.  The smaller package was opened and was found to contain an item matching the description of an item on the packing list.  The item was a metal can that contained a flammable warning on its label.  SAES Getters was contacted to retrieve an MSDS for the material.  SAES Getters was not able to produce an MSDS for the material shipped.  The only MSDS available was for the raw material used to produce the product that was shipped.  The material met the met the limited quantity exception for the PSN Metal powders, flammable, n.o.s.  The outer package should have been marked in accordance with 49 CFR requirements for overpacks.  The shipping papers should also have indicated that a limited quantity hazardous material was present.
column169: In-house response was appropriate.    The nature of shipper training and procedures is unknown.

column168: Our semi-transport was loaded with gasoline (gasohol) en route to one of our bulk plants.  The truck was west bound on US Rt 30.  A Ford Ranger pickup truck pulled out (failed to stop) in front of our truck at the intersection of St Rt 511. The impact caused the front axle of our truck to break loose of the springs; our driver was unable to control and the rig rolled over on its left side.  The semi slid on its side for approximately 50 yards.  The surface was dry concrete pavement (rough).  This caused the abrasive action that wore through the shell of the tank at each bulk head; thus all but a few hundred gallons leaked out onto the pavement.  The product ran into the median area, flowed east to a catch basin, then to buried conduit to the ditch along Rt 511, which flowed north.  Ohio DOT diked the ditch and contained a great deal of the product.  Cleanup and recovery began as soon as the unit was removed from the highway (6AM).  BBU of Zanesville, Ohio is the contractor.  Chris Bonner of the OHIO EPA was on-site and remains in contact with us and the contractor.  We are currently waiting on concrete catch basins to be built so the project can be completed.  The final report will be submitted when the the project is done and we have cost totals.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling, approximately 5 miles outside Williston, North Dakota, Falco Energy Transport LLC was struck by a train.  The vehicle involved was a truck, with a mounted tank, and attached "pup" trailer.  The mounted tank contained approximately 3,780 gallons of crude oil, and the "pup" trailer contained approximately 6,930 gallons of crude oil.  As a result of the accident, the truck and mounted tank caught fire, and were severely damaged.  However, the "pup" trailer remained in tact, with minor heat damage.  Falco Energy Transport LLC dispatched a rescue tanker to offload the crude oil from the "pup" trailer.  Approximately 3,780 gallons of crude oil were compromised, with the majority being consumed in the fire, and the remaining impact to the soil adjacent to the railroad tracks.  Burlington Northern Railyard coordinated cleanup efforts and response actions.  There were no injuries or exposures as a result of the release.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and was related to a train accident, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Falco Energy Transport will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: Cargo was tendered to Nippon Cargo Airlines in Chicago on 14Oct10 at 1035 local time. No discrepancies noted upon acceptance, storage and loading while in NCA's possession in Chicago. Upon arrival in our Tokyo warehouse, one box was noticed to be leaking and emiting an odor. Package was carefully opened and it was noticed that the bottle in question was packaged upside down inside the outer packaging. Due to the improper packaging of the bottle inside the package, the cap failed resulting in .2L of UN1262 Octances. This outer package also contained another package of UN1993 Flammable Liquid (4-Hydroxy-2-Butanone) but there was no leakage of this hazardous material. Our staff in Tokyo coordinated with the shipper's representatives in Tokyo to repackage this cargo and forward to the ultimate destination of Singapore.
column169: Upon learning of this incident, NCA in ORD held a meeting with the shipper(Sigma-Aldrich) in Milwaukee, WI. We discussed this issue in depth. As the accepting airline, we were not able to determine the way the inner contents were packaged. We emphasized to the shipper the importance of properly packing the inner contents.

column168: Load was offered to J. B. Hunt as a non-hazardous, dry goods commodity.  Intermodal container was presealed when powered.  Load was railed from MD to CA where it was discovered to not be CA-legal on weight.  Container was taken to a transloading facility where the cargo was found to lack blocking & bracing.  Upon inspecting the cargo, an electric forklift was found that was not blocked & braced and had a charged liquid battery attached.  Also found was a CO2 cylinder for a Mig welder that was unmarked, unlabeled hazardous and not marked empty per 29 CFR regulations.  J. B. Hunt grounded the materials at the transloading facility, and verified no other hazardous materials on board.  Undeclared hazmat moved no further on JBH equipment.
column169: Shipper has been permanently barred from shipping any freight with J.B. Hunt.

column168: Intermodal COFC load.  Spill occured at the receiving rail head prior to final delivery on highway.  Cargo was well blocked and braced longitutially but was not braced laterally.  A raised nail on a laminar blocking cleat in cominbination with the lack of lateral bracing and movement incidental to transportation resulted in two 5 gallon pails being punctured, leaking approxiametly 5 gallons total of Class 8 PG II.  Container was taken the the railroad's hazmat pit and neutralized by SAK Environmental of North Andover, MA acting as a subcontractor to Premium Environmental Services of Newburgh, IN.  J.B. Hunt and Norfolk Southern Lars groups have reviewed loading, blocking & bracing practices with the shipper and have been ensured shipper management will carefully inspect every hazardous materials shipment in the future to prevent a future incident.
column169: JB Hunt and our partner carrier, Norfolk Southern, have offered and given training to the shipper regarding proper loading practices.  At this time, we are satisfied the customer understands the gravity of any size of hazmat spill.

column14: New Jersey Ave & E Street SE
column168: Driver hooked up hoses to pump from IBC into customer tank. Driver checked all connections again and turned on pump. Driver started to walk away to make sure product was going into customer tank. He was about 15ft. away when he turned around and saw acid spraying from the connection at the discharge hose and pump. Driver turned off the pump to stop the product from spraying. The customer employees and driver started spreading soda ash to neutralize and contain the acid. The driver then turned off all valves and disconnected the hoses. When the driver disconnected the hoses, he saw that one of the metal ears of the 1.5" dry mate valve had broken in half causing the leak. DC Hazmat and Fire showed up on scene to take over. Environmental clean up team called in the clean up the spill.
column169: The valves on all delivery pumps and hoses will be replaced on a yearly basis.

A BNSF local train stopped on the main track with the train crew reporting entrained UTLX 208459 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) with fresh product wetness on its side shell. BNSF responders and a nearby shipper responder reported that inspection of UTLX 208459 revealed that 5 of 8 manway securement bolts were not tool tight (finger loose). UTLX 208459's loose manway securement allowed product to escape from the manway closure during rail movement. The responders properly tool tightened the loose manway securement bolts. Spillage on UTLX 208459's side shell was evaporating. Nine other like shipments from the same shipper in the train were also inspected. Two of these were also found with finger tight manway securement bolts. The responders tightened the loose manway bolts and no product was reported released from these two shipments. Afterwards, the BNSF responders reported no further product release was evident during subsequent rail movements of these rail cars.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column17: The New York, Susquehanna & Western Railway
column168: Railcars, last containing hazardous soils contaminated with hexavalent chrome, were not adequately cleaned and decontaminated at the unloading facility in Michigan as required.    The empty railcars were moved to the NYSW Railway in NJ for reloading.  Upon inspection of the railcars in the NYSW's Little Ferry yard it was determined that the cars contained some soils that may be contaminated from the previous commodity.  Rainwater coming in contact with those soils drained from the railcar thru drain holes on the bottom of the railcar.  That rain water drainage may have been contaminated.  Three railcars were found to in this condition.    The drain holes were immediately capped.  Samples were taken from the railroad right of way immediately under the drain pipes.  One of five samples tested positive for chromium.  Further testing, and remediation if necessary, to be performed.    The railcars were tarped and moved to a facility for proper cleaning and decontamination.
column169: Unloader of railcars to remove all soils from railcar, clean and decontaminate railcar as required and perform quality inspection before releasing railcar as empty for subsequent movement by railroad.

column168: On October 8, 2010, five to seven gallons of Hydrogen Peroxide impacted the asphalt during a transfer.  After the transfer was verified, the bleeder valve was opened in order to prime the equipment.  Once the equipment was primed and the transfer up and running, the loader did not close the valve.  Residual product released into the reservoir tank, resulting in a five to seven gallon release of product impacting the asphalt.  Water was applied to the affected area as per the MSDS.  After speaking with the loader who did the previous transfer on October 7, 2010, he informed the Terminal Manager that the reservoir had been filled with water during his transfer; therefore the amount of actual Hydrogen Peroxide impacting the asphalt may be less than the estimated five to seven gallons.  There were no injuries, and no drains were impacted.
column169: ROOT CAUSE:  The Loader failed to close the bleeder valve after priming the pump.  In a post incident interview the Loader stated that he was having personal issues after a recent car accident.  He was stressed over the property damage which made him lose his focus; he did not communicate this to his Supervisor at the beginning of the shift.       CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:  1. SSP 3025-006 was updated to include process of closing the valve after the pump is primed.  All employees were re-trained on updated procedure.    2. High density five gallon bucket is now being utilized under the bleeder valve on every transfer.    3. The Verifier will remind the Loader to close the bleeder valve once equipment is primed during verification.   4. Contact Shipper and TRANSFLO to discuss the possibility of obtaining a pump with a spring loaded valve which would automatically close once the valve is released after the pump is primed.    5. All employees were asked to speak up during morning safety meetings if they had any issues that would hinder their performance

column168: RESIN WAS IN PROCESS OF TRANSFERENCE FROM 3RD PARTY DELIVERY TANKER (CAPACITY 7000 GALS) VIA HOSES INTO OUR STATIONARY, JOB SITE TANKER (CAPACITY 6,400 GALS): BOTH TRANSFERENCE WERE CONDUCTED BY PUMPING. ULTIMATELY, THE RESIN WOULD BE TRANFERRED FROM OUR TANKER INTO OUR INJECTION MACHINE THAT WOULD IMPREGNATE A SEWER MAIN LINE. TO THE BEST OF OUR KNOWLEDGE AND BELIEF, THERE WAS NO APPARENT FAILURE OR CAUSE OF ANY SORT, OUR TANKER JUST TIPPED ONTO IS SIDE DURING THE PROCESS, SPILLING RESIN. LOCAL POLICE AND FIRE DEPTS. WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT AND BOTH RESPONDED, AS DID FIRE DEPT. RESCUE AND HAZ-MAT UNITS. SPILL WAS CONTAINED BY EMPLACEMENT OF SAND ALONG THE PERIMETER OF THE SPILLED RESIN. SAND WAS ALSO MIXED INTO THE RESIN TO REDUCE ANY VOLATILITY.
column169: IT MUST BE NOTED THAT IN THE DECADES OF PERFORMING THIS KIND OF WORK NATIONWIDE, IN SCORES OF PROJECTS, THIS IS THE FIRST INCIDENT OF ITS TYPE WHEREIN OUR TANKER TIPPED ONTO ITS SIDE SPILLING RESIN. column168: A BNSF train crew observed a vapor or dust cloud emanating from an entrained rail car near the head end of their train. The train was then stopped on the main track to allow the train conductor to investigate the cloud source. The conductor reported entrained HOKX 8302 (DOT 111A100W5 tank car) was leaking product that produced a strong pungent odor. BNSF and contract responders determined after their initial inspection of HOKX 8302 that the leak source near the B-end right side body bolster of this jacketed tank car was from a suspected internal liner failure. A contract responder using a 'plug kit' managed to stop the leak by 0220 hrs. CDT, 10/13/2010. Shipper representatives assisted by the contract responders transferred product from HOKX 8302 to another suitable tank car by 1400 hrs. CDT, 10/13/2010 without further incident.  Responders inserted a buffering solution inside HOKX 8302 after the product transfer was completed and also applied soda ash to neutralize spillage that impacted ballast and soil. Afterwards, HOKX 8302 was carefully moved away from main trackage and into the BNSF yard facility at Kansas City, KS. On 10/15/2010, the interior and exterior of HOKX 8302 was neutralized and water washed, resulting in neutral pH readings. Shipper was granted FRA-10100735 movement approval to transport HOKX 8302 to their facility in Wichita, KS. No further incidents were reported for HOKX 8302 during this movement on the BNSF.    The side specification stencil on HOKX 8302 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2005 and next due in 2015; the lining inspection was completed in 2008 and next due in 2013.

Driver was transferring product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  He reported that he had to use a 3" double female adaptor on the outlet of the pump for the unload.  It seemed a little loose so he shimmed it.  When he started product flowing through the pump, it squirted out the sides, missed the bucket and went on asphalt.  By time he shut down (2-3 sec) about 1 gallon had missed the bucket underneath the connection. Driver used spill pads to clean up and customer put sawdust on it, shoveled it up and put more sawdust down.  Customer gave the driver one of their fittings to complete the offload with no problem.
column169: The driver should have tried to get a different fitting instead of shimming it or at the very least, he should have started the flow of product very slowly to see if the fitting would leak or if it was secure.

column168: Driver was transferring product from cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  He had to deliver to two different tanks.  He completed the unload into the first tank but had to clear the line so he could cap the hose and take to the next tank.  he got about 1/2 gal out of the bleeder when he bled the line.  With all the valves closed, he hooked up the airline to the bleeder and the other end to the compressor.  He then opened the valve on the customer tank.  Driver had used one section of 20' product transfer hose going to the customer's fill line.  The fill line then went straight up about 10-12', over and then into top of tank. When he opened the customer valve so he could blow the lines clean, product leaked out of the air hose connection on the bleeder and the compressor.  Driver immediately went to close the customer valve because of the back flow of product from the customer line. <1 gal spilled out on the blacktop.  It was hosed into the plant containment system.
column169: Driver will be brought in for remedial training because he did not follow proper procedure for clearing a line with air.  He should have had the compressor going and then opened the customer valve last.

column168: A BNSF switchman in the railyard reported UTLX 642114 (DOT 111A100W3 tank car) leaking product from near the A-end of this jacketed tank car. UTLX 642114 was cordoned-off and containment receptacles were placed under the leak area of UTLX 642114. An interior liner failure was suspected.  Contract responders transferred product from UTLX 642114 into lined portable Frac Tanks without further incident. During the transfer process it was reported that the leak ebbed and stopped approximately half-way through the product transfer.  The Frac Tanks containing product were held at the BNSF railyard facility until a suitable tank car arrived for the transfer of the product from the Frac Tanks. On 10/22/2010, this transfer commenced and was completed without incident by 0200 hrs. CDT, 10/23/2010. Ground impact area at the initial product release site was neutralized with a soda ash-water solution.   Shipper requested and FRA Movement Approval 10100693 was granted to move residue UTLX 642114 to a cleaning facility for internal cleansing and then to a qualified repair facility for causal investigation and necessary repairs.     UTLX 642114's lining was applied at the time of the last tank qualification (06/2006).

column168: The Heritage Transport driver was pulled over for a roadside inspection conducted by the Illinois State Police. Once the truck was stopped at the Toll Booth on 1-294 SB at milepost 30 it was discovered that the trailer had a 6’ crack in the frame at axle #4. This was allowing rainwater contaminated with the PCBs to be released from the dump trailer. The driver was able to contain the release with spill pads and no material entered soil, water, or sewers. Other Heritage Transport personnel arrived on the scene and were able to move the material inside the dump and apply a seal on the inside of the dump to cease the release of materials.   It appears that when the materials were loaded into the trailer a piece of asphalt was dropped inside the trailer and caused the damage to the trailer. This also caused the liner to be ripped/torn and allow the rainwater to mix with the material.

column168: On 10/18/10 at approximately 1715 hours, while offloading a pallet of drums from a van trailer and placing them in a transportation staging area, 4 drums fell off the pallet.  One lid of one drum was comprimised which resulted in the spill.   The spilled waste was contained within the transportation staging area and was cleaned up by CHES San Jose plant technicians. The waste generated from the spill cleanup was containerized and will be managed appropriately by CHES San Jose.     The operator did not place the fork all the way in the pallet prior to lifting and tilting the pallet.  By not doing so, one board broke and the drums tilted slightly.  When placing the pallet of drums onto the floor of the transportation staging area, the tilted drums fell forward.
column169: Since the root cause of the incident was determined to be unsafe forklift operation, a review of the incident and the unsafe practices was immediately reviewed with CHES San Jose shipping and receiving technician. Forklift operator will be formally retrained in loading and unloading as well as forklift operations.

column168: On Friday, 10/22/10, Clean Harbor's Driver Richard Smith made a routine stop at Clean Harbors' ten day transfer facility where he parked his trailer at the facility's truck dock and did a post trip inspection on the unit. No problems were noted at that time.   At 0645 on Monday, 10/25/10, Clean Harbor's Truck to Truck Supervisor opened trailer #67000T to transfer the waste to a different unit. Supervisor noticed that the trailer had an odd smell, but he did not think that anything was wrong. While unloading the trailer he noticed that there was some liquid on the floor, but he thought that it was rain water. The Supervisor began to move a 55 gallon container  when he noticed that the container felt light.  At this point Supervisor took a pH reading of the material on the floor and it had a pH value of 0. Supervisor notified CHES management and advised the other employees in the facility to keep away from the affected area. The Supervisor then went to inspect the exterior of the trailer. It was noted that the material had begun to leak through the side of the van on the bottom edge near the front on the passenger side. He immediately evaluated the extent of the contamination on the ground and bermed the area off to prevent the spread of the material.   CHES management mobilized an in-house emergency response team the to scene of the spill to handle the cleanup and decontamination. The response team neutralized the acid and proceded to decon the items in the van as well as the surrounding pavement. All other waste containers on this shipment were inspected for damage and decontaminated. The only damage that was found was to pallets, not waste containers, that were near the leaking drum. The containers on the affected pallets were placed on new pallets and all debris that was created from these operations was packaged for disposal. The container that failed was inspected and found to be a non-specification drum that had developed a crack on the underside.
column169: After investigation into the circumstances surrounding this spill; it was learned a hole was most likely in the bottom of the drum.  It was also learned the drum was a non spec drum.  Driver was suspended for accepting this type of drum.  Driver will be retrained on proper packaging.    All personnel were immediately retrained on detecting a potential spill.

column168: 9:20AM-DRIVER (ERIC GOLDBERG) CALLED TERMINAL AND SPOKE TO DISPATCH (MICHAEL) SOMETHING WAS LEAKING ON TRAILER, DISPATCH CHECKED TO SEE WHAT WAS ON TRUCK AND KNOWING WE HAD HARARDOUS MATERIAL ON BOARD, ADVISED DRIVER TO GET OFF EXIT RAMP THAT HE WAS AT AND PULL OVER TO A SAFE SPOT, RIGHT OFF RAMP WAS A BIG EMPTY PARKING LOT NEXT TO A FIRE DEPARTMENT, AT THIS POINT FIRE DEPARTMENT OF MILFORD MASS TOOK OVER SITUATION.   9:45AM-SENT OUT REPRESENTATIVE FROM SAFETY COMMITTEE(ALBERT CHENEY) WENT DOWN TO THE SCENE.  9:50AM-FIRE DEPARTMENT GAVE THE OKAY FOR US TO DO CLEAN UP CALLED CYN ENVIRON. TO TAKE CARE OF CLEAN UP.  10:15AM-TALKED TO (JIM) ON SITE FROM CYN ENVIR. ADVISED THEY WERE TAKING CARE OF THE SITUATION.  1:00PM-CALLED NATIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND CHEM TREC.  1:20PM-FILLED REPORT #2010121200451 WITH CHEM TRAC (MANUFACTURERS RESPONSE COMPANY)  1:30PM-CALLED NATIONAL EMER. RESPONSE BACK TALKED TO TED EPA REGION 1, NO EVIDENCE OF ANY PRODUCT GOING INTO ANY DRAINS OR NEAR WATER, NOT SURE IF WE NEED TO MAKE A REPORT.  2:00PM-CALLED NATIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE BACK AND MADE OUT A REPORT ANYWAY. REPORT NUMBER 956742.  5:00PM-ALL CLEAN UP COMPLETED AND TRANSPORTED BY CYN ENVIRONMENTAL FOR DISPOSAL.
column169: AT OUR DIRVERS MEETING, WE HAVE DISCUSSED WHAT TO CHECK FOR WHEN PICKING UP HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IN DRUMS AND TOTES, WHAT TO LOOK FOR TO MAKE SURE DRUMS AND TOTES HAVE BEEN TESTED AND WHAT LETTERS AND NUMBERS SHOW WHAT TYPE OF PRODUCT CAN BE STORED IN THESE CONTAINERS. TO AGAIN STRESS THE IMPORTANCE OF BEING DILLIGENT WHEN HANDLING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THE TRACTOR TRAILER WAS HEADED EAST ON ROUTE 460 NEAR MONTVALE, VIRGINIA. IT WAS TRAVELING A SPEED OF 45MPH THRU A CURVY SECTION OF HIGHWAY. THE TRACTOR TRAILER ROLLED ONE TIME CAUSING THE TRAILER TO SEPERATE FROM THE TRACTOR. THE TRAILER SLID DOWN A STEEP EMBANKMENT RESTING UPSIDE DOWN. THE TRACTOR REMAINED ON THE EDGE OF THE HIGHWAY. APPROXIMATELY 4000 GALLONS OF REGULAR GASOLINE ESCAPED THRU THE DOME LIDS. A SMALL PORTION OF PRODUCT ENTERED A TRIBUTARY OF GOOSE CREEK. THE VAST MAJORITY OF PRODUCT SATURATED THE SOIL BENEATH THE TRAILER. FIVE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENTS AS WELL AS THE VIRGINIA EMERGENCY SERVICES, AND W.E.L., AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT, PADS AND BOOMS WERE PLACED ON THE TRIBUTARY AND TWO UNDER FLOW DAMS WERE CONTRUCTED TO INSURE PRODUCT WOULD NOT FLOW TO GOOSE CREEK. THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS PUMPED OFF THE TRAILER TO INSURE NO FURTHER PRODUCT WOULD ESCAPE. THE SCENE WAS SECURED AND THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE TOWED AWAY. APPROXIMATELY 187 DUMP TRUCK LOADS OF SOIL WERE REMOVED FROM THE SITE.
column169: ADDITIONAL SAFETY POLICIES AND PROCEDURES WILL BE REVIEWED AND IMPLEMENTED.

column168: On 10/30/10 at 16:22 hrs., personnel at the CSXT Barr yard in Riverdale, IL, discovered UTLX 200811, a residue tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., leaking from the bottom outlet valve. column168: On 10/31/10 at 08:00 hrs., personnel at the CSXT Barr yard in Riverdale, IL,discovered  SHPX 208891, a residue tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S, leaking from the bottom outlet valve area. The car was isolated and the shipper, East Coast Reload LLC (Kevin Kennedy 610-217-6576) was advised. Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the locking pin for the bottom outlet valve was missing, the valve was not completely closed, and the BOV cap was less than hand tight. Eagle/SWS personnel closed the valve, replaced the pin and secured the cap. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.     This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause code: 148  NARRI: 5 (4+3+0) x (2+0) = 70

column168: Transport vehicle operated by TransWood Inc. stopped on designated route at mandatory fuel stop. Truck drivers noticed a mist rising from the manifold cabinet at rear of trailer. Drivers located the vehicle down the interstate away from the public and notified dispatch of leak, called 911, evacuated the vehicle with shipping documents and HM information. TransWood notified MEMC and PCS of leaking trailer. TransWood then dispatched Eagle Environmental (contracted response) to the site. TransWood then reported incident to LA State Police and Chemtrec. Police, fire and ambulance responded.MEMC indicates the following cause of failure: The packing on the #4 tube valve failed causing the leak. It was determined that the packing nut on the valve was not tight.
column169: TransWood Inc. can make no recommendations to prevent future occurrences. The manifold cabinet is sealed for shipment whether loaded by PCS in Aurora NC or empty from MEMC Corporation in Pasadena TX. Please find Attachment A, a photo document of the transport vehicle in question and the interior of same manifold Cabinet. MEMC indicated: All trailers are pressure tested before loading and after unloading. In addition to pressure testing they checked the packing nut on all trailers to ensure they were tightened properly.

column168: On 10/25/2010 at 0848, AGR crew on northbound manifest train struck a tree at MP 629.5 and derailed both head-end locomotives and 13 cars, approximately 17 miles south of Armory, MS. Three tank cars contained hydrogen peroxide (TILX 200051, TILX 200131 and PROX 42160). Two of the hydrogen peroxide cars were leaning (TILX 200051 and TILX 200131) and leaked from the continuous vent valves. PROX 42160 did not appear to leak, however, 280 Ibs. of lading were unaccounted for after the product transfer. The lading that leaked evaporated completely leaving no residue or required cleanup at the location. The three tank cars were uprighted and moved for transloading. They were transloaded on 10/28/2010 & 10/29/2010.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: The driver reported this spill to N&M Transfer at approximately 2:40 p.m.  CST on Tuesday, October 26, 2010.  At the time of the call the driver had just pulled out of the dock at USA Docu-Finish, Plainfield, IL.  The driver reported that there were some liquids on the bottom of the skids of freight that had just been delivered at USA Docu-Finish.  He also reported that liquids were coming out of the nose wall and side wall areas of the front of his trailer.  The driver was told to park the trailer away from the building in the lot at Docu-Finish.  The driver was instructed to take out his spillkit and apply pads and pillows to the perimeter ground surface around the tractor-trailer.  A response contractor was called within thirty minutes of the notification by the driver.  At the time of the spill the driver had three shipments on the trailer.  A hazardous materials shipment was discovered to contain the 55-gallon drum which was leaking.  After the response company entered the trailer they discovered that the drum had been creased, crushed and cracked about six inches from the bottom of the drum. (See photos. Also see loading diagram of this trailer.)  The hazardous materials shipment contained sixteen drums, with four drums loaded on each skid.  Each skid had wrapped shrink-wrap around the drums and the corners of the skids. The drum that released was loaded on the driver side of the trailer, on the front side of the pallet, loaded closest to the trailer wall.  This pallet was loaded up tight against a pallet of a carton of broom supplies.  There were no obstructions or sharp edges from the trailer floor, wall or broom pallet.  As a result of these observations, we can only conclude that the N&M Transfer dock employee who loaded this trailer punctured this drum while loading the trailer.  We believe the dock loader may have done this in an attempt to push the drum back on the pallet because some of these pallets were noted as having the drums beginning to slide over the edges of the pallet.
column169: The investigation materials noted in this spill report (diagrams, photos, observation notes) are being forwarded to our dock manager to conduct an investigation of how this trailer was loaded.  We found that two different dock employees were involved in the loading process of this trailer.  They will both be interviewed and asked how they loaded this trailer.  If N&M Transfer concludes that either one or both of these employees played a part in the improper loading of this trailer, they will face disciplinary action, up to and including suspension of employment.  Regardless of whether or not the dock loaders are found at fault for the improper loading of this trailer, both employees will also receive follow-up training from our dock trainer.

column168: TRUCK DRIVER WAS GOING TO MAKE DELIVERY AT LOCATION OF SPILL, WHICH IS A GASOLINE STATION. THE STATIONS PARKING LOT AND FUEL ISLAND IS WELL BELOW THE ROADWAYS GRASS. THE DRIVEWAY IS ON AN INCLINE WHICH IS STEEP AND SHORT. THERE IS AN APPROX. DROP OF APPROX 3 TO 4 FT OVER AN APPROX 12 FEET LENGTH. THE DRIVER WAS BACKING INTO THE STORE FROM THE ROADWAY IN ORDER TO MAKE THE DELIVERY. DRIVER HAS TO MAKE A TURN WHILE DOING THIS. WHEN INCIDENT OCCURED, THE SEMI-TRAILERS WERE STILL ON THE HIGH PORTION OF DRIVERS TOAR THE INCLINE STARTS DOWN. THE DRIVER MADE A MID-TURN CORRECTION WHICH PUT THE TRACTOR-TRAILER IN A TIGHTER TURN ANGLE THAN USUAL. AS HE DID THIS-DUE TO THE INCLINE OF THE DRIVEWAY, THE LEFT REAR FRAME MEMBER STRUCK AND PUSHED ON THE TRAILERS RIGHT SIDE FRAME MEMBER. THIS IMPACT CAUSED THE TRAILERS FRAME MEMBER TO BREAK AND TEAR AT THE PLACE WHERE IT WAS WELDED TO THE TANK BARRER. THE WELD BROKE AND ALSO WHEN IT BROKE, IT TORE A SMALL RIP INTO THE TANK'S BARRER WHICH CAUSED A SMALL LEAK OF PRODUCT. THE RIP WAS APPROX 2" LONG AND VERY NARROW. LEAK STOPPED BY UNCAPPING THE COMPARTMENT. SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP. PRODUCT CONTAINED ON A PAVED/CONCRETE AREA-THERE WAS NO SOIL CONTAMINATION.
column169: SHORT-STOOP INCLINES LIKE THIS CAN ALWAYS POSE A HAZARD TO TRACTOR-TRAILERS. BETTER BUILING PLANNING AND CROSS COULD BE USED FOR COMMERCIAL BUSINESSES THAT REQUIRE TRACTOR-TRAILERS TO ENTER THEIR PROPERTY FOR DELIVERY, ETC, TO ELIMINATE THIS TYPE OF STOOP CHANGE OVER A VERY SHORT LENGTH. OUR DRIVERS ARE TRAINED ON THIS TYPE OF HAZARD AND THERE IS RECURRING TRAINING ON THIS TOPIC IN SAFETY MEETINGS.

column168: While loading freight into trailer material handler went to pickup a pallet with boxes of paint on it and while doing so he noticed one of the boxes was slightly leaking. Further investigation revealed that the box must have been hit by a forklift or other freight while temporarily staged on the dock which eventually led and contributed to the unintentional release. The trailer was loaded at the shipper and was enroute when the driver stopped at a company terminal in Chattanooga, TN to take his rest break.  When the driver performed a pre-trip inspection a drip of product was noticed.  A bucket was placed under the drip.  The product was transferred into another trailer.  Less than 5 gallons was collected in the bucket.    The empty trailer was cleaned and transported to Polar in Houston, Texas for inspection and repair.  The inspection revealed that trailer 7117 had a crack in the barrel near the steam pads at the front side of the tandems.  It was discovered that the steam pad had been welded continuesly along the length of the steam pad.  This allowed no expansion room.  It is beleived that has steam was applied additional stress was applied to the barrel due to temperature differential.  This developed a hairline crack in the shell.
column169: Steam pads will be examined to ensure gaps in weld are in place to allow for expanison.  Steam temperature will be controlled to limit the rate of temperature change.

column168: PACKAGE RADIOACTIVE SURFACE CONTAMINATION INCIDENT IN ACCESS OF REPORTING LIMITS The GE Healthcare facility while receiving a package containing UN2910, detected removable radioactive surface contamination on the outer surface of the package greater than the reporting limits of 220 dpm/cm2. The package contained returned materials (lead-lined syringe containers) that were being shipped back to the GE Health care facility from a customer location in Rochester Hills, Michigan.The incoming package contamination (583 dpm/cm2 Tc-99m) was identified during the routine radioactive package receiving process by GE Healthcare personnel. The suspect package was secured in the facility and the site Radiation Safety Officer (RSO) initiated an investigation into the origin of the contamination. Radioactive contamination surveys were performed on the facility Receiving Area, GE Healthcare personnel, and the GE Healthcare vehicle that transported the package. All radioactive contamination surveys completed were at or below background. The package contents (0.082 uCi) were allowed to decay to background levels and then physically inspected to determine if the cause of the package contamination was a package integrity failure. The packaging was found to be intact without any physical defects present. The in-house GE Healthcare package contamination incident investigation concerning the origin of the radioactive contamination was deemed inconclusive.
column169: After the GE Healthcare facility conducted an initial in-house investigation of the package contamination incident, the Shipper (Cardiology & Vascular Associates) was notified of the elevated removable surface contamination on the outer surface of the package which was >220 dpm/cm2. GE Healthcare informed the Shipper (Cardiology & Vascular Associates) the package radioactive contamination incident was reported to the National Response Center and the Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC) Command Center in accordance with 49 CFR 171.15(b)(2).The Shipper was encouraged to provide staff re-training on returning UN2910 package shipments to GE Healthcare and improving internal hazardous material shipping procedures to prevent any future recurrence.

ON OCTOBER 25, 2010, AT 1130 HOURS, VEOLIA ES SPECIAL SERVICES, INC. (VES-SS) RECEIVED A CALL FROM DIANE DREYMALA WITH CHARTIS INSURANCE REGARDING A DIESEL FUEL RELEASE. THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AT THE SAIA MOTOR FREIGHT TERMINAL LOCATED ON 5424 NE 14TH STREET IN DES MOINES, IOWA. AN ESTIMATED 75 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS RELEASED TO THE ASPHALT LOT FROM AN INCIDENT INVOLVING A SOLAR TRANSPORT TRACTOR AT TERMINAL. TERMINAL PERSONNEL CONTAINED THE RELEASE WITH FLOOR DRY. VES-SS SUBCONTRACTED J. PETTIECORD, INC. TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT AND PERFORM THE NECESSARY CLEAN UP.    AT 1230 HOURS, J. PETTIECORD, INC. PERSONNEL ARRIVED ONSITE AND MET WITH THE TERMINAL MANAGER. AN INSPECTION OF THE SITE FOUND CONTAMINATED FLOOR DRY UNDERNEATH AND AROUND A DIESEL FUEL STORAGE TANK AND ON THE ASPHALT. THE CONTAMINATED FLOOR DRY WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED IN DRUMS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. ADDITIONAL FLOOR DRY WAS APPLIED TO THE SPILL AREA TO REMOVE THE REMAINING RESIDUE ON THE ASPHALT SURFACE. THIS MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED AND PLACED IN THE WASTE DRUMS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. A TOTAL OF SIX 55 GALLON DRUMS OF WASTE WERE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE CLEAN UP.     AS THE ASPHALT WAS SERVERELY CRACKED, A SECTION OF ABSORBENT BOOM WAS PLACED ON THE LOWER END OF THE SPILL AREA. THIS WAS DONE AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE TO ABSORB AND CONTAIN ANY DIESEL FUEL THAT MAY LEACH FROM THE CRACKS DURING A RAIN EVENT.    AT 1600 HOURS, J. PETTIECORD, INC. PERSONNEL WERE OFFSITE.    THE SIX DRUMS OF WASTE WERE TAKEN TO HYDROCLEAN IN DES MOINES, IOWA FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column168: At 0940 on 10/21/2010, an employee noticed a leaking hose on a Portable Tank of AC-55-5. The employee notified a member of the HazMat Response Team. Rolando Salvo. Rolando responded to the area and visually inspected the leaking hose. Rolando left the area to gather HazMat supplies and don the appropriate Personal Protective Equipment. During this time, a Whey Department Supervisor, Frank Castro, was conducting his daily rounds of the exterior and noticed the hose connecting the portable tank to the CIP system was leaking. He went inside to notify his Supervisor at 1015. Rolando and Frank returned to the tanker at the same time and saw that the hose had broken loose at the camlock connection. Rolando attempted to turn off the hand valve at the Tanker, but it was stuck in place. Rolando then turned off the ball valve to the tanker, stopping the flow of AC-55-5 from the tanker. The tanker had been leaking for 7 minutes, which is the time between Frank seeing the leak and his return. The HazMat team was notified for spill cleanup at this point. The AC-55-5 had not reached any drains; the drains were covered with appropriate HazMat drain covers to prevent any contamination. Sodium Bicarbonate was applied to the spilled acid as a neutralizer. The pH of the solution was tested and was at a 7.0. The solution was then rinsed into a central location, where the solution was pumped into our on-site treatment facility.   A follow-up investigation revealed that the venting sequence had overpressurized the tanker, causing the hose connection to leak. The hose was secured with plastic zip ties, which were melted by the AC-55-5.
column169: The following steps have been taken to prevent recurrence:   1. Venting sequence has been reprogrammed so that the vent valve opens for 20 seconds before the pot fill valve opens.   2. There will be a Whey Department employee at the tanker at all times when the outlet valve is open. a. This employee will have a radio and full Personal Protective Equipment (PPE).   b. This employee has been trained what to do and who to notify in the event of a spill. 3. Only stainless steel zip ties will be allowed to hold the camlock connection in place.

column168: Due to human error our delivery driver overfilled by 50 gallons an underground unleaded fuel storage tank at the Arrowmart Convenence store located in Ashville, New York at approximately 06:30 on 10/12/10. The release itself lasted only a few seconds. Upon discovery, store personnel notified emergency responders. the release was also reported immediately to the New York State Department of Environmental Conservation (Spill # 1007429). Flow of the spill did reach 2 storm drains that border the property. These drains flow to a small feeder creek (unknown name) that flows to Chatauqua Lake. Emergency responders did place spill booms and pads at the outlet to the creek to prevent any flow of contamination from reaching the lake. Due to recent dry weather though, contamination never reached the creek, it settled in the storm drain piping. Both storm drains were flushed with water provided by the Lakewood Fire Department. OP-TECH Environmental utilized a vacuum truck to suck the contaminated water from another storm drain before it reached the creek. Both storm drains were flushed until totally free of contamination. The resulting contaminted water was then drummed (12 drums total). The clean spill pads from the creek, speedi dri used to clean the residual fuel on the parking lot surface and dirty spill pads from the parking lot were drummed (5 drums total) for disposal as well. Lastly there was one drum of sludge that was cleaned from the bottom of the vacuum truck which included leaves and debris that was in the storm drains. The total count of drums for disposal was 18. Sentinel Technologies provided disposal of the drums on 10/21/10. The total amount of time spent remediating this spill was approximately 10 hours from arrival on scene to finish.
column169: On the date of the Spill the Delivery Driver (Chris Martin) was counseled on appropriate delivery procedures during delivery. It was discovered that he had not measured the level in the undergournd fuel tank prior to the delivery. If he had done so, he would have discovered it could not hold the amount he was attempting to delivery. Beyond that all of our delivery drivers were called to a meeting in which proper delivery procedures were reaffirmed. Likewise, drivers were all instructed to if possible avoid pakring their delivery trucks over the tank pad. This will help them to see a spill as it happens allowing for quicker response. Since this spill was the result of huma error at our delivery level, we do not believe that there is any industry level control that could be put in place to prevent this from happening.

column168: On 10/26/20 10 at 1:35 AM, the Galena Park Gulf Region Kinder Morgan Liquids Terminal LLC (KM) began transferring toluene from tank 25-13 to a railcar located on track 4 spot 12. At approximately 2:20 AM, operations observed that toluene was spilling from the top of the railcar to the immediate area below/near the railcar. Further investigation revealed that our customer shipped Kinder Morgan a full railcar when the bill of lading (BOL) indicated the car was empty. This contributed to the railcar overfilled and ensuing spill.   KM took immediate action by initiating an emergency shutdown of the transfer operation. Once the operation was stopped, KM performed area safety monitoring, responders donned the proper personnel protective equipment and recovered/mitigated the spilled product using absorbent pads and a vacuum truck. During day-light hours on 10/26/10 KM began remediation of the impacted spill area by removing the contaminated soil. Kinder Morgan has met with our customer informing them of the incident and the importance of completing the BOL accurately. Our customer is working on their business practices to ensure accurate information is provided to Kinder Morgan on the BOL. Kinder Morgan is using the incident as a “lessons learned” event to ensure that the BOL documentation along with other site practices and procedures confirm a car is ready to be filled prior to beginning a railcar loading operation.
column169: KM response: Events leading up to the spill that caused the emission event were as follows:   a) Customer BOL Incorrect - The Kinder Morgan Liquids Terminal (KM) is a for hire liquid storage facility. We depend on our customers to provide appropriate documentation concerning railcars delivered to our terminal. In this event, the railcar Bill of Lading (BOL) received by KM from our customer indicated the railcar was empty.   Corrective Action: Worked with Customer to ensure proper BOL identifying condition of rail cars received.   b) Railroad Online System - Prior to loadings railcar it is KM’s practice to confirm the status of the railcar is empty using the Railroad’s online system. The railroad online system also showed the railcar empty when in fact the railcar was shipped full to KM.   Corrective Action: Operator responsible for loading railcar was coached on the importance of following site practices and procedures.   c) Kinder Morgan Railcar Liquid Level Manual Check - It is KM’s practice to visually check the liquid level in a railcar prior to loading. During the investigation it was determined that the operator may not have accurately visually gauge the railcar liquid level.   Corrective Action: Operator responsible for loading railcar was coached on the importance of following site practices and procedures.   d) Kinder Morgan Liquid Level Probe (Scully Probe) - During the investigation, it was determined that the Scully Probe was not placed in the railcar prior to filling.   Corrective Action: Operator responsible for loading railcar was coached on the importance of following site practices and procedures.   If any of the above events been identified prior to loading the railcar, the spill and ensuing emission event may have been avoided.
